<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-245-141 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 820 643</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Jan 10 1991 v36 n1A p29(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moving into management? Pay attention to politics, people, and topbrass. (advice for engineers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ward, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Engineers who move into management must cope with theresponsibility of managing former peers.andP;  The move also requiresstronger interpersonal skills, paying greater attention to companypolitics and more responsibilities.andP;  A mentor can make thetransition easier.andP;  For many engineers, improving interpersonalskills is the greatest challenge.andP;  New managers who make a bumpystart should not panic; trial and error is the only sure teacher.andO;Building relations with other company officials is a must; to dothat, the new manager must learn to leave details to others.andP;  Agood manager must delegate duties and learn to rely on the staff'sexpertise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Career DevelopmentPromotion of EmployeeJob ResponsibilityManagement DevelopmentEngineeringGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>